Preheat the #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Chop the @potatoes{600%g} into 2cm chunks. Place in a #pot{}, cover with @water{to taste} and season with @salt{to taste}.

Bring to the boil and cook until fork tender, ~{12-18%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} (reserving some cooking water) and return to the pot, off the heat.

Add a knob of @butter{to taste} and a splash of milk or cooking water. Mash until smooth with a #potato masher{}. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Cover to keep warm.

Meanwhile, remove the packaging from the @Irish Pulled Pork{300%g} and pop into an #oven dish{}.

Cover with #foil{} and cook for ~{25-30%minutes}. IMPORTANT: Ensure the pork is piping hot throughout.

Meanwhile, trim the @carrot{1}(trimmed, no need to peel), then coarsely grate.

Peel and grate the @garlic{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Cut the @tomato{1} into 1cm chunks.

Place a pan over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{1%tbsp}.

Once hot, add the grated carrot. Fry until starting to colour, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Add the garlic to the carrot and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Stir the @passata{1%pack}, @cranberry chutney{1%sachet}, @dried thyme{1%sachet}, @chicken stock{1%sachet}, @salt{1/2%tsp} and @water{50%ml} into the pan.

Bring to the boil, then lower the heat to medium.

Simmer until thickened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Once thickened, remove the pan from the heat.

When the pork is ready, drain the cooking liquid into a #bowl{}.

Shred the pork with two #forks{} while still in the oven dish.

Add the simmered sauce and 2 tbsp of the reserved cooking water then mix well to combine.

Spread the mash over the top in an even layer, using the back of a #spoon{} to smooth it out.

Place the pie on the top shelf of the oven to warm, ~{5-6%minutes}.

While the pie warms, mix @oil{1%tbsp} with the @balsamic glaze{1%sachet} in a #salad bowl{}.

Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Just before serving, add the @salad leaves{40%g} and tomato to the bowl with the dressing. Toss to combine.

Once cooked, share the pork pie between plates.

Serve the tomato salad alongside.